snippet.textDisplay: In every town I've lived in in the south - six of them - and every state - two of them - and every state in the south I've visited - almost all thirteen of them (born in SC) - they claim that all southern cooking is the same and universal (it's not), that their version of every recipe is the "right" one (different everywhere you go) - ditto with dialect, traditions, supersitions, phrases and famous expresions - it's all tribal BS. Me in Charleston, SC: "OK - what's sawmill gravy?" (silence - doesn't know. Almost everybody in TN does). Me, in western NC: "OK, what's hoppin' John?" (silence - doesn't know. Almost everybody in Charleston does). My neighbors in WNC: if you're a real southerner you put sugar on your grits (ditto in central TX). Charlestonion: "sugar on your grits!!! - you F'in yankee !". My neighbor in Charleston: "Trout fishin' is a yankee sport !!" My neighbor in WNC, where trout is King: "wanna go trout fishin'?" Folks - it's all BS. The Myth of The South is that any such place exists. It's all politics and revisionist history. The best one? The "always polite" southerner (a really obnoxious myth). Me in a convenience store in WNC: "Thank you." The hometown clerk: "umhmm!" (why I love WNC: SOO much more genuine and less fake than Charleston!!!! :-)
snippet.textOriginal: In every town I've lived in in the south - six of them - and every state - two of them - and every state in the south I've visited - almost all thirteen of them (born in SC) - they claim that all southern cooking is the same and universal (it's not), that _their_ version of every recipe is the "right" one (different everywhere you go) - ditto with dialect, traditions, supersitions, phrases and famous expresions - it's all tribal BS. Me in Charleston, SC: "OK - what's sawmill gravy?" (silence - doesn't know. Almost everybody in TN does). Me, in western NC: "OK, what's hoppin' John?" (silence - doesn't know. Almost everybody in Charleston does). My neighbors in WNC: if you're a _real_ southerner you put sugar on your grits (ditto in central TX). Charlestonion: "sugar on your grits!!! - you F'in _yankee_ !". My neighbor in Charleston: "Trout fishin' is a _yankee sport_ !!" My neighbor in WNC, where trout is King: "wanna go trout fishin'?" Folks - it's _all_ BS. The Myth of The South is that any such place exists. It's all politics and revisionist history. The best one? The "always polite" southerner (a really obnoxious myth). Me in a convenience store in WNC: "Thank you." The hometown clerk: "umhmm!" (why I love WNC: SOO much more genuine and less fake than Charleston!!!! :-)
